scular volume","Uraemia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn chronic kidney disease, several factors contribute to bone disease, but \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary cause of increased fracture risk. As kidney function declines, there is decreased production of active vitamin D and phosphate retention. This leads to secondary hyperparathyroidism, where the parathyroid glands increase hormone production to maintain calcium homeostasis. The elevated parathyroid hormone causes increased bone resorption and demineralisation, making bones more susceptible to fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Euraemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause various complications, it does not directly cause bone fragility. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased vascular volume\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the cardiovascular system. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnaemia\u003C/strong\u003E in CKD results from decreased erythropoietin production. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is common in CKD but does not contribute to fracture risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic kidney disease causes secondary hyperparathyroidism which leads to bone demineralisation and increased fracture risk.","Secondary hyperparathyroidism occurs due to decreased vitamin D activation and phosphate retention in chronic kidney disease."],"references":["Chen TK, Knicely DH, Grams ME. Chronic Kidney Disease Diagnosis and Management: A Review. JAMA. 2019 Oct 1;322(13):1294-1304. doi: 10.1001/jama.2019.14745. PMID: 31573641; PMCID: PMC7015670","Vaidya SR, Aeddula NR. Chronic Kidney Disease. [Updated 2024 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535404/","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66095"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15108"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66095"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T08:14:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T08:14:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7796"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80776"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonym